<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="499" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,977,1940]" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1049,1075]" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Gorochov, 1994" authorityName="Gorochov" authorityYear="1994" box="[655,992,1049,1075]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Mitius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="499" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="enatus">
<emphasis box="[655,805,1050,1075]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">Mitius enatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gorochov, A. V." box="[810,992,1049,1075]" pageId="7" pageNumber="499" pagination="3 - 15" refId="ref5644" refString="Gorochov, A. V. (1994) Materials on the fauna of Gryllinae (Orthoptera, Gryllidae) of Vietnam. Part 2. In: Gorochov, A. V. &amp; Kireichuk, A. G. (Eds.), News of systematics and faunistics of Vietnam insects Part 4. Proceedings of the Zoological Institute of the Russian Academy of Sciences, 257, pp. 3 - 15. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1994">Gorochov, 1994</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs from the latter in that it lacks hind wings; the apex of lateral lobes of epiphallus not bifurcated, and the apex of middle lobe broad and round.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="499" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,977,1940]" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,416,1121,1147]" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">Description. Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[435,504,1121,1147]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1415,1439]" captionTargetBox="[160,1430,188,1364]" captionTargetId="figure-19@8.[151,1436,180,1374]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. Mitius eryuanensis Yuan, Xie &amp; Liu sp. nov. 1. male; 2. female. Scale bars: 2.0 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5057424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5057424/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Body size small, covered with pubescence. Head (
<figureCitation box="[1121,1191,1121,1147]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–6" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1166,1190]" captionTargetBox="[157,1430,187,1138]" captionTargetId="figure-36@9.[151,1436,181,1142]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 3–6. Mitius eryuanensis Yuan, Xie &amp; Liu sp. nov. 3, 4. Head, frontal view; 5, 6. Supra anal plate, dorsal view. 3, 5. Male; 4, 6. Female. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5057426" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5057426/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) nearly globular and smooth. Frontal rostrum slightly protruding and wide, about 2.5 times as wide as the scapus; eyes weakly protruding, and longitudinally ovoid; ocelli rather distinctly, median ocellus transverse ovoid; lateral ocelli nearly round. Fronto-clypeal suture convex, and the middle part arc-shaped; last joint of maxillary palpus slightly stout and shorter than 4 
<superScript attach="left" box="[309,322,1265,1279]" fontSize="6" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">th</superScript>
joint; last joint of labial palpus swollen and horseshoe-shaped. Pronotum transverse, anterior and posterior margin almost straight and same width, almost equal to the width of head; lateral margin of disk slightly straight, 1.5 times as the anterior margin. Tegmina reaching to middle part of the 10 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1073,1086,1337,1351]" fontSize="6" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">th</superScript>
abdominal tergite, present with 2 oblique veins; mirror rather small, rhomboid, without dividing vein; hind wings absence. Fore tibiae with oblong external tympanum, without internal tympanum. Hind tibia with 4 internal spines, 5 external spines, apex separately 3 spurs, lower spur smallest; first tarsi longer, about 2.5 times as long as 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[980,996,1445,1459]" fontSize="6" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">nd</superScript>
joint, with two rows of small spines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,977,1940]" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">
Supra anal plate (
<figureCitation box="[392,457,1481,1508]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–6" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1166,1190]" captionTargetBox="[157,1430,187,1138]" captionTargetId="figure-36@9.[151,1436,181,1142]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 3–6. Mitius eryuanensis Yuan, Xie &amp; Liu sp. nov. 3, 4. Head, frontal view; 5, 6. Supra anal plate, dorsal view. 3, 5. Male; 4, 6. Female. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5057426" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5057426/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) trapezoid, distinctly narrowed posteriorly; dorsal surface of plate uneven, with a nearly circular indentation in the middle. Subgenital plate rather long, coniform. Genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[1115,1226,1517,1543]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1815,1839]" captionTargetBox="[152,1424,1251,1791]" captionTargetId="figure-71@9.[151,1436,1251,1792]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Mitius eryuanensis Yuan, Xie &amp; Liu sp. nov. Male: genitalia (7. dorsal view; 8. ventral view; 9. lateral view). Scale bar: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5057428" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5057428/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">Figs. 7–9</figureCitation>
): epiphallus rather short, with two lateral lobes and one small middle lobe; apex of lateral lobes blunt and slightly bent upward in lateral view; middle lobe small, with wide and round apex; ectoparameres no reaching to apex of middle lobe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,977,1940]" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,286,1625,1651]" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">Female</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[301,370,1625,1651]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1415,1439]" captionTargetBox="[160,1430,188,1364]" captionTargetId="figure-19@8.[151,1436,180,1374]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. Mitius eryuanensis Yuan, Xie &amp; Liu sp. nov. 1. male; 2. female. Scale bars: 2.0 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5057424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5057424/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Body slightly larger than male. Tegmina nearly reaching to 8 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1067,1080,1625,1639]" fontSize="6" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">th</superScript>
tergite of abdomen, dorsal field with several parallel longitudinal veins, cross veins sparse. Supra anal plate (
<figureCitation box="[1030,1099,1661,1688]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–6" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1166,1190]" captionTargetBox="[157,1430,187,1138]" captionTargetId="figure-36@9.[151,1436,181,1142]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 3–6. Mitius eryuanensis Yuan, Xie &amp; Liu sp. nov. 3, 4. Head, frontal view; 5, 6. Supra anal plate, dorsal view. 3, 5. Male; 4, 6. Female. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5057426" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5057426/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) very similar to that of male. Ovipositor short and straight, about 0.8 times as long as length of hind femur, apex acute.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,977,1940]" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1733,1759]" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">Coloration.</emphasis>
Body brown, tegmina black brown. All coxa, trochanters and most femora yellow, and the others brown to black brown. Ovipositor brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,977,1940]" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,456,1805,1831]" pageId="7" pageNumber="499">Measurements (mm).</emphasis>
Male: body 10.5–11.0, pronotum width 2.5–3.0, length 1.7–2.7, tegmina 4.9–5.0; female: body 12.2–13.0, pronotum width:3.2–3.5, length:2.2–2.5, tegmina 4.5–4.8, ovipositor5.5–6.0.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
